<div class="flex flex-col gap-5">
	<p>
		Sara Ludy approaches nature as a field of perception rather than something to capture or represent. After three decades working with digital materials, her practice exists in what she calls a “postdigital era,” where screens and landscapes, simulation and sensation, fold into embodied vision. “There isn’t a line, there’s a field,” she says of the boundary between real and virtual. Her work emerges from “tuning into a signal”—an intuitive process where the charged atmosphere of New Mexico’s Sandia Mountains, along with visions and dreams, surfaces through whichever medium calls in the moment.
	</p>
	<p>
		This strategic fluidity resists the scientific authority embedded in environmental media. Where nature documentaries promise clarity through data and observation, Ludy offers opacity as method. Abstraction becomes a way to hold impressions “without pinning them down,” refusing the language that fixes nature into knowable categories. Her correlation between inner simulations and digital simulations reveals something beyond materiality: “It carries a different presence, a lightness, something that speaks more to the inner world, the imagination, even the third eye.” In her practice, nature is consciousness-dependent, fragmented, and irreducible to any single form of seeing.
	</p>
</div>
